For this tutorial, I plan to revisit main concepts of the Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) test and implement it with R. ANOVA tests estimate how a quantitative dependent variable changes according to the levels of one or more categorical independent variables. In other words, using ANOVA, we can determine whether there is a statistically significant difference in the means of the groups with regards to the variable in question.
To conduct ANOVA test with a real-world example, I will use Olympic Medals dataset from TidyTuesday-Week 32 challenge. This dataset includes information on athletes participated in summer or winter games since Athens 1896 to Rio 2016. In this analysis, I will subset the whole dataset to the ones only received a gold medal in the games. So, the dependent variable will be the medal variable subsetted to the gold, retrieving the information only for athletes who won a gold medal in the games. For the independent variable, I will categorize athletes’ height into three different classes; short (&lt;170 cm), medium (in between 170 cm and 185 cm), and tall (&gt; 185 cm). Therefore, what will be inquired is to see whether there is a statistically significant difference across gold medal-winning athletes having different heights (Tall/Medium/Short).
